    {
      "id": "jshell-201-intro",
      "type": "MARKDOWN",
      "mode": "jshell",
      "source": "# JShell 201 — Collections & Data Structures\n\nJava provides a rich **Collections Framework** with well-tested, highly-optimized data structures. Knowing which one to reach for is a core Java skill.\n\n| Structure | Use when… | Key trait |\n|---|---|---|\n| `Array` | size is fixed, type is primitive | fast index access, fixed size |\n| `ArrayList` | ordered list, size can grow | fast random access by index |\n| `LinkedList` | frequent insert/delete at ends | fast add/remove, slow index lookup |\n| `HashMap` | key → value lookup | O(1) average get/put |\n| `TreeMap` | key → value, keys sorted | O(log n), keys in natural order |\n| `HashSet` | unique elements, no order needed | O(1) contains check |\n| `TreeSet` | unique elements, sorted | O(log n), sorted iteration |\n\nThis notebook focuses on the ones you'll use 90% of the time: **Array, ArrayList, HashMap, HashSet**.",
      "output": "",
      "returnValue": null,
